This paper is about improving the performance of artificial neural networks for visual recognition tasks. The paper focuses on the HMAX architecture, which is commonly used in computer vision, and proposes a new approach using locality-constrained linear coding (LLC) instead of sparse coding (SC). This suggests that the paper is likely to be categorized under computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of signal whitening, spot detection, and spatial pyramid matching, which are all techniques commonly used in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and neural networks (cs.NE). Finally, the paper also mentions the use of GPUs for training, which is a common technique in multimedia (cs.MM) research.
